South African Journal of Botany

Volume 112, September 2017, Pages 1-10

Relationships and genetic structure of North African barley (Hordeum vulgare L.) germplasm revealed by morphological and molecular markers: Biogeographical considerations

    Assessment of genetic diversity of barley in North Africa

  • â€¢

    Genetic structure and relationships among barley landraces

Abstract

Landraces represent a crucial reservoir of gene pool for crop improvement and a valuable germplasm for sustainable agriculture towards climate change. To establish conservation strategies for barley germplasm, 31 North African landraces were characterized by associating morphogenetic data with molecular markers. Partial relationships were found between divergence pattern and geographic origin at morphological level, while molecular dendrogram clearly separated barley landraces into two major groups based on geographic distribution. Grain yield, glum awn and lemma awn barb appear to be the most discriminative agro-morphological traits required for exploitation of these valuable resources. A total of 114 amplification products were scored by RAPD primers exhibiting an overall 84.85% polymorphism. Molecular variance demonstrated that genetic variation was partitioned within (60.31%) rather than between (39.69%) the populations. Data showed considerable gene flow (Nm = 1.439) and moderate genetic differentiation (GST = 0.257) with highest diversity observed in Tunisian and Egyptian populations. No significant correlation was found between the distance matrices based on molecular and morphological data indicating no influence of genetic background on the observed morphological variation. These results reinforce the integration of both morphogenetic and RAPD markers as a starting point for in situ conservation of these accessions allowing adaptation to local environments.

1. Introduction

Barley is one of the main important cereal crops worldwide cultivated in all temperate areas. Ranking fourth in world cereal production, it is mainly used for animal feed, brewing malts and human consumption (Bothmer et al., 2003). Cultivated barley (Hordeum vulgare L.) was domesticated from its wild relative (Hordeum spontaneum C. Koch) as early as 7.000 BC (Salamini et al., 2002) which is originated from the Fertile Crescent and diversified within the Himalayas and the Tibet (Badr et al., 2000, Morrell and Clegg, 2007). So far, strong evidences showed that cultivated barley may have multiple origins and suggested the horn of Africa as a center of barley diversification and likely a potential domestication site (Orabi et al., 2007) along with North Africa as possible secondary centers of barley origin (Tanno et al., 2002, Molina-Cano et al., 2005). During this process of domestication, barley has gradually accumulated key traits â€“ selection for non-brittle rachis, six-rowed spikes and naked caryopsis â€“ that facilitated agriculture production (Salamini et al., 2002). Additional conscious modifications included increase in seed number, size and shape, improved seed fertility, reduced dormancy requirements, photoperiod insensitivity, flowering adaptation to different areas, and loss of seed shattering (see for review, Pourkheirandish and Komatsuda, 2007). Natural selection associated with human selection during centuries resulted in those landraces that have developed abundant patterns of variation for qualitative and quantitative characters and also have good adaptation to specific environmental conditions (Bothmer et al., 2003).

Barley landraces are genetically heterogeneous populations; no crossing barriers have been developed between the wild and cultivated forms, therefore spontaneous and artificial crosses are easily obtained (Asfaw and von Bothmer, 1990). The genetic structure of those landraces may be considered as an evolutionary approach towards performance under arid and semi-arid zones. In this context, barley has been found to show wide genetic variation alongside a high tolerance to drought (Zhao et al., 2010) and salinity stress (Qiu et al., 2011, Allel et al., 2016), as well as it would represent a largely unexploited reservoir of useful candidate genes for abiotic stress tolerance (Brush, 1995).

The survey of barley germplasm at a molecular basis is a prerequisite for its efficient exploitation in breeding programs. Such genetic diversity assessment of barley landraces originating from various geographic areas has been investigated based on morphological traits and/or molecular markers (Dakir et al., 2002, Pandey, 2006, Manjunatha et al., 2007, Jilal, 2011). However, difficulties in the identification of closely related genotypes using only morphological descriptors (IPGRI, IBPGR or UPOV) have increased with the development of new varieties, and since these descriptors are sometimes influenced by environment rather than genetics (Tanto Hadado et al., 2009). Furthermore, biochemical characterization that relies on variation among isoenzymes (Laugesen et al., 2007) and seed storage proteins (Dakir et al., 2002, Canci et al., 2003) has been used, while these kinds of markers were not suitable due to the low level of allelic variation in many isoenzymatic loci.

Alternatively, the development of a wide range of PCR-based DNA markers (RFLP, AFLPs, RAPDs, ISSRs and SNPs) and their use in genome analysis has provided unprecedented insight into structural features of the barley genome (Hamza et al., 2004, Guasmi et al., 2012). Genetic mapping is highly valuable to localize economically important traits and to develop closely linked markers to these traits useful for marker-assisted selection (Pandey, 2006). Since years, RAPD fingerprinting has been an increasingly used marker system in studies related to plant genetic resources and has a number of potential applications including determination of cultivar's purity, management of germplasm variability and genetic relationships (Hoffman and Bregitzer, 1996). Because of its simplicity, effectiveness, low cost and easily handling, the RAPD has been extensively employed in assessing genetic diversity in DNA sequences and applied for efficient and rapid genotyping of hundreds of specimens either in wild (Baum et al., 1997, Nevo et al., 1998, Owuor et al., 2003) or in cultivated barley (Strelchenko et al., 1999, Terzi et al., 2001, Dakir et al., 2002, Manjunatha et al., 2007).

Studying North Africa's barley accessions at morphological and molecular level will be helpful for understanding their genetic diversity, for managing their conservation and their effective use in agriculture. During the last years, genetic studies of barley populations within North African countries (Dakir et al., 2002, Hamza et al., 2004, Mohamed et al., 2010, Zoghlami et al., 2011, Guasmi et al., 2012, Allel et al., 2016) showed various tolerance sources for abiotic stresses with high food quality. Nonetheless, the data generated are often limited to single country and thus gave an incomplete overview of the genetic structure of barley landraces in North Africa making their relationships and their exact origin still unknown.

In this regard, investigating the association between the agro/morphological characterization-based genetic variation and the use of molecular approach could be an essential component to understand the genetic structure of barley germplasm. The goal of this study is to assess levels and patterns of genetic variability among a collection of barley genotypes from the North Africa using morphological and molecular markers.

2. Materials and methods

2.1. Plant collection

Barley material consisted of 31 landraces (accessions and varieties) collected from some North African countries (Tunisia, Algeria and Egypt) with different agroclimatic conditions (Table 1). These genotypes were collected from various geographical regions and mainly from arid and semi-arid areas. The material included 27 hulled and 4 naked barleys.

2.2. Morphological characterization

The experiment was carried out in a randomized block design with 9 replications under controlled greenhouse conditions. Each main plot contained the 31 genotypes. At sowing, three seeds were used in each pot (5 kg). After germination, each pot was thinned to one seedling. A total of 41 morphological descriptors including 18 qualitative and 23 quantitative characters, mainly defined by the International Plant Genetic Resources Institute (IPGRI) were used (see Table 2, section Results).

2.3. DNA isolation and RAPD analysis

Total genomic DNA was extracted from young leaf tissues following the CTAB procedure described by Doyle and Doyle (1987). Plant leaves from 9 replicates were pooled together to represent a DNA sample of each accession. Subsequently, the DNA quantity and quality were determined by both spectrophotometry at 260 nm and by 1.5% agarose gel electrophoresis. PCR conditions were optimized to generate reproducible PCR amplification profiles. RAPD analysis was carried out with twelve decamer random primers from Operon Technologies Inc. (see Table 3, section Results). Primers giving clear and polymorphic amplification patterns were selected to assess genetic diversity of the 31 specimens of barley collection. Each PCR reaction was repeated twice to ensure reproducibility. The PCR reaction mixture was carried out in a volume of 15 Î¼l and consisted of 25â€“50 ng of genomic DNA as template, 1 Ã— reaction buffer (10 mM Trisâ€“HCl, pH 8.3 and 50 mM KCl), 2.0 mM MgCl2, 1 U of Go-Taq DNA polymerase (Promega, Madison, USA), 200 Î¼M of each dNTP, and 0.8 Î¼M of oligonucleotide primer. Amplifications were achieved using the GeneAmp 9700 thermocycler (Applied Biosystems, USA) with cycling program including initial denaturation at 94 Â°C for 5 min, followed by 45 cycles: denaturation at 93 Â°C for 1 min, annealing at 37 Â°C for 1 min and extension at 72 Â°C for 2 min with final extension at 72 Â°C for 7 min. Amplification products were fractionated on 1.5% agarose gel. The list of primers used and their annealing temperatures are presented in Table 3. The amplification products were visualized in an ultraviolet transilluminator after horizontal electrophoresis in 1.5% agarose gel in TAE buffer. DNA was stained with ethidium bromide and irradiated in UV light with the use of DI-HD-220 imaging system (Major science, CA, USA).

2.4. Data analysis

Data were recorded on 9 randomly chosen plants per plot. Analysis of variance was performed for all measured traits (agronomic traits) in order to test the significance of variance among genotypes. Two sets of data, morphologic traits and molecular markers, were generated and used to evaluate the genetic variability.

RAPD bands were scored as either present (1) or absent (0). Subsequently, scores were entered into a binary rectangular matrix on the subprogram NTedit of NTSYSpc v.2.10e program (Exeter Software, Setauket, N.Y.) (Rohlf, 2000). From these data a similarity matrix based on Dice coefficient (Nei and Li, 1979) was calculated. The similarity matrix was run on module SAHN (sequential, agglomerative, hierarchical, and nested) (Sneath and Sokal, 1973) by using the Unweighted Pair Group Method with Arithmetic Average (UPGMA) clustering algorithm (Sokal and Michener, 1958) to generate the respective dendrogram. The polymorphic index (PIC) of each marker was calculated using the formula PIC = 1 âˆ’ Î£Pi2 where Pi is the band frequency of the allele (Smith et al., 1997). These PIC values were used to calculate the RAPD primer index by adding all the PIC values of all markers amplified by same primer (Raina et al., 2001) and divided by the total number of markers. The following genetic parameters were calculated using POPGENE version 1.32 (Yeh Francis and Rong-Cai, 1999): the percentage of polymorphic loci (PP), observed number of alleles per locus (Na), effective number of alleles per locus (Ne), and Nei's (Nei, 1972) gene diversity (h) (Lewontin, 1972). The degree of polymorphism was quantified using Shannon's index (I) of phenotypic diversity (Shannon and Weaver, 1949).

To analyze the organization of variability within H. vulgare landraces, we examined the genetic variation by partitioning the total genetic diversity (HT) into an intra-population component (HS) and an inter-population one (GST). Furthermore, gene flow (Nm) between the pairs of populations was calculated from GST values by Nm = 0.5(1 âˆ• GST) âˆ• GST (Slatkin, 1987). To examine the genetic relationships between populations, Nei and Li (1979) genetic distance was also generated by POPGENE. Molecular data were analyzed using multivariate analysis, ANOVA analysis using XLSTAT software (Addinsoft, http://www.xlstat.com). The correlation between the Euclidean distance matrices based on morphological and RAPD data was tested for significance using the Mantel test by 1000 permutations.

3. Results

3.1. Morphological characterization

3.1.1. Agro-morphological variation

In this study, morphological data were used to investigate the genetic diversity among 31 barley accessions and varieties. Variance analysis revealed highly significant differences between barley genotypes for all the quantitative variables. Their corresponding mean values measured for all barley genotypes are presented in Table 2 and showed a wide polymorphism for all quantitative traits. In fact, our data demonstrated a highest grain yield, grain number per plant and whole plant biomass production achieved from Tunisian accessions Kebili2, Kairouan and Tozeur2, while the lowest one was Early1 from Egypt. Compared to other genotypes, phenological traits illustrated that Early1 and Early2 were the earlier flowering and maturing accessions. The difference between the minimum and the maximum was higher in all traits studied.

Regarding qualitative traits; although all genotypes were likely similar for some characters (six rowed except for Early1 and Early2, awned, with yellow glume, yellow awn, lemma hair, amber lemma, yellow grain), genetic variation within accessions was found. Fig. 1 showed pronounced differences between barley accessions for inflorescence traits. In fact, wide diversity of the morphogenetic spike traits was observed (e.g. spike length, grain density and awn length). In our case, most of the accessions collected in North Africa were covered; naked barley had low frequency and including Tombari from Tunisia, Azrir from Algeria, Giza129 and Giza130 from Egypt. Moreover, our traits studied presented a clear divergence between 2 sets: Tunisian/Algerian versus Egyptian group. Within the first pool, barley spikes were generally characterized by short rachilla hair, rough lemma awn barb and length of glume plus glume awn as long as kernel. While, spikes from Egypt had mainly long rachilla hair (73%), heterogeneous lemma awn barbs (66.5% rough and 36.5% intermediate) and glume plus awn longer than or nearly twice as long as kernel, respectively. The highest 1000 grain weight was recorded in Algerian genotypes: Ksar-Megarine and Tichedrett. The aleurone color was found as a trait that could discriminate barley population derived from distinct origin. In this regard, aleurone was blue for Egyptian accessions, white for Algerian and mixed (blue or white) for Tunisian populations.

3.1.2. Cluster analysis of morphometric traits

The pair-wise similarity values of morphometric data obtained within the 31 landraces of barley ranged from 0.834 to 0.998. Based on Jaccard's similarity coefficients, a maximum similarity value was observed between T5 and T7 accessions, indicating an important genetic similarity between them. Conversely, T1 and A3 genotypes displayed the lowest similarity coefficient. Average similarity across all landraces was 0.916. As revealed by UPGMA clustering, all accessions were classified into three clusters (Fig. 2a). Hereafter, two major groups comprised 18 and 12 accessions respectively; Early2 genotype formed a group by itself. Agronomically superior barley landraces were included in cluster I which named as a high yielding cluster group. This cluster consists mainly of six rowed type with high yield potential (grain yield and spike dry weight), high filling capacity (high spikelet and grain number per plant/per spike), high heading capacity (high spike number), high tillering capacity, high shoot and whole plant biomass production and high leaf production. In contrast, the second cluster named as low yielding cluster group was characterized by low grain yield with small vegetative part production. This cluster was the most discriminative.

Based on morphological data, cluster analysis assigned the landraces from the same region, city or country in the same subgroup. This fact was shown for Egyptian landraces with two subgroups: Giza131, Giza123 and Giza2000 along with Giza126 and Giza127. Similar results were found for Algerian (Tichedrett and Saida) and Tunisian landraces (Kerkennah and Kebili) which are grouped in the same subgroup respectively (Fig. 2a). In addition, it was observed elsewhere that genotypes from neighboring countries (Tunisia and Algeria) were clustered together in two minor groups which reflect a close relationship based on geographical proximity. The first one contained: Nailia, Tozeur1, Tozeur2, Ras El Mouch and Temassine. The second group comprised: Tichedrett, Saida, Sidi Bouzid, Ksar-Megarine and Tombari.

3.2. RAPD profiling

3.2.1. Assessment of discriminating capacity of RAPD markers

Thirty one barley varieties and accessions were chosen for RAPD polymorphism. Among 12 decamer oligonucleotides selected, 10 yielded a positive and repeatable banding pattern of amplification products and thus were selected for the RAPD analysis. PCR amplification of the genomic DNA isolated from the 31 barley accessions yielded a total of 132 bands, of which 114 were polymorphic (86.36%) and 18 were monomorphic (Table 3). Overall size of the PCR amplified fragments ranged from 200 to 2750 bp. The banding pattern of barley genotypes has been shown for the primers OPB-01, OPA-04 and OPA-11 (Fig. 3). The total number of amplified DNA bands ranged from 9 (OPC 10) to 18 (OPA 11), with an average of 13.2 bands per primer. The present study showed a relatively high level of polymorphism (60.16%) across all the 31 barley landraces ranged from 41% (primer OPA-11) to 76.8% (OPC-06).

3.2.2. Population genetic structure and level of genetic diversity in barley

Data showed that the average gene diversity (HT) (Nei and Roychoudhury, 1974) over all loci was 0.258. The average expected heterozygosity (HS) across all loci in the total sample was 0.200. The observed number of allele (Na) per population varied from 1.55 to 1.59 (Table 4) and for all populations is 1.85. The mean effective number of allele (Ne) (Kimura and Weiss, 1964) for all populations was 1.41 with a range from 1.33 to 1.38. Populations from Tunisia (population 1) had the largest value of Ne and h while the population from Egypt (population 3) had the lowest (Table 4). Across the three populations of barley surveyed for RAPD variation, Nei's (1973) estimator of population substructure (GST) indicated a relatively high level of population differentiation (GST = 0.257). These GST values translated into correspondingly low levels of gene flow (Nm), with 1.43 migrants exchanged between populations (on average) each generation (Table 5). Shannon's index partitioned 38.1% of the total variation between populations, in broad agreement with the result of genetic differentiation analysis.

3.2.3. Genetic diversity and relationships

The pair-wise similarity values obtained between the 31 landraces of barley ranged from 0.530 to 0.916. From the analysis of Jaccard's similarity coefficients, a maximum similarity value was observed between A3 and A4 cultivars, indicating an important genetic similarity between them, whereas T7 and E7 cultivars showed the lowest similarity coefficient. Average similarity across all the cultivars was 0.723. The dendrogram grouped all the 31 landraces into two major clusters (Fig. 2b). The first cluster was the biggest comprising 20 genotypes containing Tunisian and Algerian landraces grouped together. The second cluster consists mainly of 11 genotypes from Egypt, except for the accession A9 that was assigned as included into this second group. The variance components of the individualized groups detected with ANOVA have shown that most of the genetic variation was partitioned within (60.31%) rather than between (39.69%) the groups, these were both significant at p < 0.001 (Table 3). A weak correlation was found between similarity matrices based on morphological and RAPD markers (r = 0.032; p = 0.492).

The relationships among populations were also evaluated using Nei's unbiased distance matrix (Table 6). The distance between groups' similarity matrix showed that the high divergence among population appears when population 1 (Tunisia) and population 3 (Egypt) are compared with each other. In contrast, Nei's genetic identity coefficient among population 1 (Tunisia) to population 2 (Algeria) was higher (0.956), while the corresponding genetic distance was lower (0.044) since Tunisia and Algeria represent neighboring countries. GST value indicates whether the majority of genetic variation is within a population or among populations. GST value near to 1.0 indicates a majority of genetic variability among populations. Conversely, a lower GST value suggests a majority of genetic variability within a given population. The GST value was 0.257, indicating that 25.7% of gene differentiation occurred among barley populations and 74.3% occurred within populations. These results indicate a relatively high level of genetic differentiation within the populations. The Mantel test of data for three populations showed no significant correlation between genetic distances and corresponding morphological distances (R2 = 0.001, p = 0.492).

4. Discussion

Genetic diversity among barley germplasm collected from North Africa was evaluated with the association of molecular marker data with morphogenetic traits which act as a beneficial tool in varietal development particularly when there is no reported QTL data available on this particular species. The data indicated that six-row materials remain prevalent, as in other North African countries (Yasuda et al., 1993, Dakir et al., 2002). Barleys with naked caryopses are found at low frequencies in our North African collection. Similar results were reported by Saisho and Purugganan (2007). The characterization revealed wide variation among barley landraces in almost all morphological characteristics (qualitative and quantitative traits) studied as indicated in Table 3. This can be explained by the evolution of these landraces in distinct agro-climatic regions, suggesting significant levels of variation in response to selection pressure as reported by several authors (Singh et al., 1998, Souframanien and Gopalakrishna, 2004). Moreover, cluster analysis showed a slight relationship between the geographic origin of populations and their divergence as illustrated in the morphological dendrogram (Fig. 2a). Genetic divergence among barley populations through cluster analysis was described previously (Bahrman et al., 1999, Hamza et al., 2004, Eshghi and Akhundova, 2010) suggesting that the variability can be partially attributed to geographic isolation, founder effects, and microclimatic differences within countries.

In this study, some qualitative characters based on IPGRI descriptors seem to be related to geographic provenance. Regarding morphological characterization, our results showed a definite dissimilarity between the set of accessions from Egypt and the set including both Tunisian and Algerian genotypes for the following traits: the lemma awn barbs, the length of glume and glume awn and the length of rachilla hair. Some traits were country-related: i.e. lemma awn barbs from Tunisia and Algeria, which are neighboring countries, were generally rough, while Egyptian collection was heterogeneous and containing some accessions with lemma awn barbs intermediate. In the same way, the length of glume and glume awn was generally as long as kernel for Tunisia and Algeria, whereas accessions from Egypt had commonly glume plus awn longer than or nearly twice as long as kernel. Similarly, we observed short rachilla hair for Tunisian and Algerian landraces while the majority of Egyptian genotypes had long rachilla hair. Taking together, we selected some qualitative traits â€“ such as number of rows and fragility of rachis â€“ useful as discriminating tools that could provide key characters for yield improvement. The grain yield is particularly important and constitutes the main objective in breeding programs. Hence, three key traits â€“ selection for non-brittle rachis, six-rowed spike and naked caryopsis â€“ were involved in barley domestication (Zohary and Hopf, 2000, Salamini et al., 2002, Barabashi et al., 2012). In this way, the present study showed that cluster analysis using morphological traits discriminated clearly high and low-yielding barley. Barley with high biomass production (grouped in cluster I) was far away from low biomass production group (cluster II) which seems to be the nearest to the barley origin ancestor. The naked barleys included in cluster II were poor yielding as well as poor thousand kernel weight. Previous reports have demonstrated that the naked gene has multiple effects on many traits, like yield reduction and lower seed weight and suggested a closer relationship of naked barley with the ancestor providing an obvious implication that naked accessions have been diverged for long time ago from the barley progenitor (Choo et al., 2001, Pourkheirandish and Komatsuda, 2007, Barabashi et al., 2012).

Morphological markers are prone to equivocal interpretations and are time-consuming to assess, not always available for analysis, and affected by environmental conditions. Therefore, PCR-based molecular marker technology is receiving much attention and has several advantages over the single use of conventional markers in cultivar identification and breeding programs. Here, RAPD was used as it remains a valuable approach to assess genetic diversity and to discriminate between barley accessions (Fernandez et al., 2002, Tanyolac, 2003, Guasmi et al., 2012). RAPD-based monitoring of the genetic variability of North African barley collection demonstrated high polymorphism among genotypes. This finding was noted also in rice (Saker et al., 2005) and orange (Lamine and Mliki, 2015) stating that RAPD markers were commonly used to discriminate minimal divergence between clones, sometimes more efficiently than SSR markers in the capacity of revealing more informative data for characterizing closely related accessions. In fact, several studies dealing with comparison of molecular markers for fingerprinting purpose found that the efficiency of RAPD compared to other structural and gene-targeted markers was relatively the same and that there were no significant differences among them, highlighting that RAPD technique was recommended in previous and recent investigations as efficient tool in terms of genotypic evaluation in various plant species (McGregor et al., 2000, Arif et al., 2009, Gorji et al., 2011, Izzatullayeva et al., 2014, Lamine and Mliki, 2015, Vaja et al., 2016). In the other hand, some current studies reported that using RAPD individually or combined with other markers does not bring supplementary information for establishing genetic relationship among studied cultivars or accessions (Gorji et al., 2011, Lamine and Mliki, 2015, Ntuli et al., 2015, Thakur et al., 2016).

In our study, the dendrogram constructed using UPGMA from RAPD-based genetic similarity matrix showed that group structure is dependent on geographical distribution. As expected, clustering highlighted accessions with the same geographic origin. Specifically, molecular data distinguished two major groups; landraces from the western part of the distribution area (Tunisia and Algeria) were assigned together into the same group, and a second group was comprised of geographically distant accessions from the east (i.e. Egypt). This pattern of geographically-related grouping by molecular markers has also been described in wheat (Ates SÃ¶nmezoglu et al., 2012) and summer squash (Ntuli et al., 2015). However, our data do not agree with previous reports on barley and Aegilops (Strelchenko et al., 1999, Owuor et al., 2003, Mahjoub et al., 2009) which state that barley does not cluster molecularly in ways that reflect geographic provenance. RAPD profiling was also effective in discriminating between naked and covered barleys; the UPGMA tree for the second cluster comprised of Egyptian genotypes, showed a separate subgroup that included naked barleys, (Giza129 and Giza130) and that appeared distinct from covered barleys as described by Manjunatha et al. (2007).

The hulled or naked caryopsis character of barley is an important agronomic trait because of its direct link to dietary use. The remains of naked kernels dating from about 8000 BP have been found in Ali Kosh, which indicates that a mutation for this trait occurred early in the domestication process of barley (Helbaek, 1969). Accordingly, Murphy and Witcombe (1986) suggested that naked barleys arose from covered barleys via a single gene mutation a long time ago, and that thereafter cultural and adaptive selection pressures caused these forms to diverge. Additionally, based on combined results connecting molecular with quantitative data, RAPD markers were suitable to differentiate accessions according to the glume awn type. Effectively, as shown with the RAPD-dendrogram (Fig. 2b), the Egyptian cluster (cluster II) was subdivided to three major subgroups which is in agreement with differentially-structured glume awn. This finding suggested the significance of RAPD markers connected with gene-related traits involved in quality and phenotypic characters that could help to give us new insights towards marker-assisted selection in barley.

Furthermore, the results gave highly polymorphic profiles showing 132 polymorphic bands detected by 10 RAPD primers and revealing a high percentage of polymorphic loci (60.16%). Similar level of polymorphism (62%) has been found by Dakir et al. (2002) in Morrocan barley. Our data displayed 86% of polymorphic bands which is in accordance with other previous reports in barley (Mohamed et al., 2010, Zoghlami et al., 2011) that stated 93% of polymorphic bands in landraces from Egypt and 88% in those from Tunisia. In this respect, the level of genetic diversity at RAPD markers is generally comparable to diversity levels described for barley landraces (Koebner et al., 2002, Zoghlami et al., 2011). The level of genetic differentiation could be highly affected by long-term selection, genetic drift or genetic isolation of populations (Francisco-Ortega et al., 2000, Poets et al., 2016). Gene flow is a critical determinant of population genetic structure. The GST-derived Nm value of 1.43 is indicative of considerable gene flow between natural populations, when compared with other studies on barley (Bellucci et al., 2013) and this value is slightly above the level (Nm â‰ˆ 1) needed to counteract genetic drift (Slatkin, 1987). Almost no correlation was obtained between morphological and molecular similarity matrices suggesting that both approaches should be investigated as complementary tools for characterization of such barley germplasm.

5. Conclusion

Morphological and RAPD-based clusters and their accompanying analyses showed different hierarchical patterns of genetic diversity among the accessions. Despite their disparity, the two approaches were found independently useful for assessing the degree of relatedness and the overall patterns of genetic variation among the analyzed barley cultivars. However, molecular markers provide powerful tools in the evaluation of intra-specific relationship and were more effective in grouping barley genotypes. Investigating the genetic structure of barley germplasm of some North African countries based on phenotypic and molecular variability remains of significant importance for genetic improvement and elite gene exploitation. Furthermore, techniques and obtained data are expected to be applicable for further works, such as marker-assisted breeding, genetic comparative mapping and association studies.
